## The Big Picture

A language model does one thing: **given some text, predict the next character** (or word, or token).

That's it. Every LLM -- GPT-4, Claude, LLaMA -- is fundamentally a next-token predictor. The magic is that by getting really good at predicting the next token, the model learns grammar, facts, reasoning, and style.

In this series of notebooks, you'll build one from scratch. Not a toy -- a real GPT, the same architecture behind GPT-2, trained on Shakespeare. By the end, it will generate text like:

```
ROMEO:
What shall I swear by? Thou art all my world:
And yet no doubt thou know'st my love is young.
```

We're following Andrej Karpathy's [nanoGPT](https://github.com/karpathy/nanoGPT), but in Elixir with Nx instead of Python with PyTorch.

## The Shakespeare Dataset

Our training data is ~1MB of Shakespeare plays. The model will learn to write Shakespeare-like text by predicting one character at a time.

```elixir
# Download the dataset
shakespeare_url = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/karpathy/char-rnn/master/data/tinyshakespeare/input.txt"
{:ok, {{_, 200, _}, _, body}} = :httpc.request(:get, {~c"#{shakespeare_url}", []}, [], body_format: :binary)
text = IO.iodata_to_binary(body)

IO.puts("Dataset size: #{String.length(text)} characters")
IO.puts("\nFirst 200 characters:")
IO.puts(String.slice(text, 0, 200))
```

## Visualize: Character Frequency Distribution

Not all characters are equally common. Space and 'e' dominate. This distribution is the first thing the model must learn.

```elixir
freqs =
  text
  |> String.graphemes()
  |> Enum.frequencies()
  |> Enum.sort_by(fn {_ch, count} -> -count end)
  |> Enum.take(30)
  |> Enum.map(fn {ch, count} ->
    label = case ch do
      " " -> "SPACE"
      "\n" -> "\\n"
      c -> c
    end
    %{"char" => label, "count" => count}
  end)

Vl.new(width: 600, height: 300, title: "Top 30 Character Frequencies in Shakespeare")
|> Vl.data_from_values(freqs)
|> Vl.mark(:bar)
|> Vl.encode_field(:x, "char", type: :nominal, sort: "-y", title: "Character")
|> Vl.encode_field(:y, "count", type: :quantitative, title: "Frequency")
```

## Character-Level Tokenization

Before the model can process text, we need to convert characters into numbers. This is called **tokenization**.

Real LLMs use sophisticated tokenizers that split text into subwords (like "un" + "break" + "able"). We use the simplest possible tokenizer: each unique character gets a number.

```elixir
# Get all unique characters, sorted
chars = text |> String.to_charlist() |> Enum.uniq() |> Enum.sort()
vocab_size = length(chars)
IO.puts("Vocabulary: #{List.to_string(chars)}")
IO.puts("Vocab size: #{vocab_size}")
```

### Exercise: Build the Encoder and Decoder

A tokenizer needs two functions:
- **encode**: string → list of integers
- **decode**: list of integers → string

The mapping is simple: each character gets an index based on its sorted position.

```elixir
# YOUR CODE: create stoi (character -> index) and itos (index -> character) maps
# Hint: Enum.with_index/1 and Map.new/2 are your friends

stoi = nil  # TODO: %{?a => 0, ?b => 1, ...}
itos = nil  # TODO: %{0 => ?a, 1 => ?b, ...}

# Test it
IO.inspect(Map.get(stoi, ?h), label: "h encodes to")
Map.get(itos, 0)
|> List.wrap()
|> to_string()
|> IO.inspect(label: "0 decodes to")
```

<details>
<summary>Solution</summary>

```elixir
stoi = chars |> Enum.with_index() |> Map.new()
itos = chars |> Enum.with_index() |> Map.new(fn {ch, i} -> {i, ch} end)
```

</details>

```elixir
# Now build encode and decode functions

encode = fn text ->
  # TODO: convert a string to a list of token IDs
  nil
end

decode = fn ids ->
  # TODO: convert a list of token IDs back to a string
  nil
end

# Test
encoded = encode.("hello")
IO.inspect(encoded, label: "encoded 'hello'", charlists: :as_lists)
decoded = decode.(encoded)
IO.inspect(decoded, label: "decoded back")
```

<details>
<summary>Solution</summary>

```elixir
encode = fn text ->
  text |> String.to_charlist() |> Enum.map(&Map.fetch!(stoi, &1))
end

decode = fn ids ->
  ids |> Enum.map(&Map.fetch!(itos, &1)) |> List.to_string()
end
```

</details>

## From Text to Tensors

Neural networks work with **tensors**, not Elixir lists. Before we convert our text, let's understand what a tensor is.

### Nx Mini-Lesson: Tensors vs Lists

In Elixir, you work with lists: `[1, 2, 3]`. In Nx, the equivalent is a **tensor** -- a typed, fixed-shape array that can live on a GPU.

```elixir
# An Elixir list -- flexible, mixed types, lives in process memory
list = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
IO.inspect(list, label: "Elixir list")
IO.inspect(length(list), label: "length")

# An Nx tensor -- typed, fixed shape, can live on GPU
tensor = Nx.tensor([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])
IO.inspect(tensor, label: "Nx tensor")
IO.inspect(Nx.shape(tensor), label: "shape (like length, but returns a tuple)")
IO.inspect(Nx.type(tensor), label: "type (every element has the same type)")
```

Three key differences from lists:

1. **Type is uniform.** Every element has the same numeric type: `:s32` (signed 32-bit integer), `:f32` (32-bit float), etc. You choose it with `type:`.
2. **Shape replaces length.** `Nx.shape/1` returns a tuple like `{5}` for 1D, `{3, 4}` for 2D (3 rows, 4 columns).
3. **Values are tensors, not numbers.** `tensor[0]` returns a 0-dimensional *tensor*, not an Elixir integer. Use `Nx.to_number/1` or `Nx.to_flat_list/1` to escape back to Elixir.

```elixir
t = Nx.tensor([10, 20, 30])

IO.inspect(t[0], label: "t[0] — still a tensor!")
IO.inspect(Nx.to_number(t[0]), label: "Nx.to_number — an Elixir integer")
IO.inspect(Nx.to_flat_list(t), label: "Nx.to_flat_list — an Elixir list")
```

Why tensors instead of lists? GPUs process millions of numbers in parallel, but only if they're all the same type in a contiguous block of memory. Elixir lists are linked nodes scattered in memory -- GPUs can't touch them.

Now let's convert our encoded text into a tensor:

```elixir
# Encode the full text and convert to a tensor
# type: :s32 means "signed 32-bit integer" — our token IDs are integers
data = encode.(text) |> Nx.tensor(type: :s32)
IO.inspect(Nx.shape(data), label: "data shape")
IO.inspect(data[0..9], label: "first 10 tokens")
```

## Train/Val Split

We split the data 90/10 into training and validation sets. The model trains on the training set; we measure how well it generalizes on the validation set (data it's never seen).

```elixir
n = Nx.axis_size(data, 0)
split_at = trunc(n * 0.9)

train_data = Nx.slice(data, [0], [split_at])
val_data = Nx.slice(data, [split_at], [n - split_at])

IO.puts("Train tokens: #{Nx.axis_size(train_data, 0)}")
IO.puts("Val tokens: #{Nx.axis_size(val_data, 0)}")
```

## What Does "Predict the Next Token" Mean?

Given a sequence of characters, the model should predict what comes next at **every position**.

For example, with the sequence `"hello"`:
- Given `h` → predict `e`
- Given `he` → predict `l`
- Given `hel` → predict `l`
- Given `hell` → predict `o`

We do this with input/target pairs where the target is just the input shifted by one position:

```elixir
block_size = 8  # context length: how many characters the model sees at once

x = train_data[0..block_size-1]
y = train_data[1..block_size]

IO.puts("Input:  #{inspect(Nx.to_flat_list(x))} = `#{decode.(Nx.to_flat_list(x))}`")
IO.puts("Target:  #{inspect(Nx.to_flat_list(y))} = `#{decode.(Nx.to_flat_list(y))}`")
IO.puts("")

for i <- 0..(block_size - 1) do
  context = Nx.to_flat_list(x[0..i])
  target = Nx.to_number(y[i])
  IO.puts("when context is #{inspect(context)} or `#{decode.(context)}` → target is #{target} ('#{decode.([target])}')")
end
```

## Batching

We don't train on one sequence at a time -- we train on **batches** of sequences in parallel. This is faster and leads to more stable gradient estimates.

### Exercise: Build a Batch

Write a function that, given the data tensor and a PRNG key, generates a random batch of input/target pairs. We'll build this up one piece at a time.

**Step 1: Pick random start positions**

> **Nx Bridge**: In Elixir, you'd pick random numbers with `Enum.map(1..n, fn _ -> :rand.uniform(max) end)`.
> In Nx, we write `{starts, _key} = Nx.Random.randint(key, 0, max, shape: {n})`.
> This returns a **tensor** of `n` random integers AND a new PRNG key. Nx uses functional PRNG -- you pass a key in and get a new one out, so results are always reproducible. (Why? GPU code can't use hidden process state like `:rand` does -- explicit keys make randomness deterministic and parallelizable.)

```elixir
batch_size = 4
block_size = 8

data_len = Nx.axis_size(train_data, 0)
max_start = data_len - block_size

key = Nx.Random.key(42)
{starts, _new_key} = Nx.Random.randint(key, 0, max_start, shape: {batch_size})
IO.inspect(starts, label: "4 random start positions")
```

**Step 2: Slice one sequence from the data**

> **Nx Bridge**: `Nx.slice(tensor, [start], [length])` extracts a contiguous chunk -- like `Enum.slice(list, start, length)`. One wrinkle: `starts[i]` returns a 0-dimensional *tensor* (not a plain integer), but that's fine -- `Nx.slice` accepts tensors as start positions.

```elixir
# Grab one sequence starting at starts[0]
x_one = Nx.slice(train_data, [starts[0]], [block_size])
y_one = Nx.slice(train_data, [Nx.add(starts[0], 1)], [block_size])

IO.inspect(Nx.to_flat_list(x_one), label: "x (input)")
IO.inspect(Nx.to_flat_list(y_one), label: "y (target, shifted by 1)")
```

**Step 3: Do it for all batch_size sequences**

```elixir
# Same thing, but for each of the 4 start positions
x_rows = for i <- 0..(batch_size - 1), do: Nx.slice(train_data, [starts[i]], [block_size])
y_rows = for i <- 0..(batch_size - 1), do: Nx.slice(train_data, [Nx.add(starts[i], 1)], [block_size])

IO.inspect(length(x_rows), label: "number of rows")
IO.inspect(Nx.shape(hd(x_rows)), label: "shape of each row")
```

**Step 4: Stack rows into a single batch tensor**

> **Nx Bridge**: `Nx.stack(list_of_tensors)` combines a list of same-shaped tensors into one tensor with a new leading dimension. Four `{8}` tensors become one `{4, 8}` tensor -- like building a 2D grid from rows.

```elixir
x = Nx.stack(x_rows)
y = Nx.stack(y_rows)

IO.inspect(Nx.shape(x), label: "x batch shape")
IO.inspect(Nx.shape(y), label: "y batch shape")
```

**Putting it together**: Now wrap steps 1-4 into a reusable function.

```elixir
get_batch = fn data, key ->
  data_len = Nx.axis_size(data, 0)
  max_start = data_len - block_size
  {starts, _} = Nx.Random.randint(key, 0, max_start, shape: {batch_size})

  x_rows = for i <- 0..(batch_size - 1), do: Nx.slice(data, [starts[i]], [block_size])
  y_rows = for i <- 0..(batch_size - 1), do: Nx.slice(data, [Nx.add(starts[i], 1)], [block_size])

  {Nx.stack(x_rows), Nx.stack(y_rows)}
end

key = Nx.Random.key(42)
{x, y} = get_batch.(train_data, key)
IO.inspect(Nx.shape(x), label: "x shape")
IO.inspect(Nx.shape(y), label: "y shape")
```

## Break It: What If Batches Aren't Random?

What happens if every batch starts at position 0 instead of a random position? The model only ever sees the first `block_size` tokens and overfits to them.

```elixir
# Always start at position 0 -- no randomness
fixed_x = Nx.stack(List.duplicate(Nx.slice(train_data, [0], [block_size]), batch_size))
fixed_y = Nx.stack(List.duplicate(Nx.slice(train_data, [1], [block_size]), batch_size))

IO.puts("Fixed batch -- always the same #{batch_size} identical sequences:")
IO.inspect(Nx.to_flat_list(fixed_x[0]), label: "x[0] (same every time)")

# Random batch -- different every call
key1 = Nx.Random.key(1)
key2 = Nx.Random.key(2)
{rand_x1, _} = get_batch.(train_data, key1)
{rand_x2, _} = get_batch.(train_data, key2)

IO.puts("\nRandom batches -- different every time:")
IO.inspect(Nx.to_flat_list(rand_x1[0]), label: "batch 1, x[0]")
IO.inspect(Nx.to_flat_list(rand_x2[0]), label: "batch 2, x[0]")
IO.puts("\nWith fixed batches, the model memorizes one passage.")
IO.puts("With random batches, it sees the whole dataset and learns general patterns.")
```

## What's Next

We now have:
- A dataset of Shakespeare text
- A character-level tokenizer (encode/decode)
- A way to generate training batches

In the next notebook, we'll build the first neural network component: **embeddings** -- the layer that converts token IDs into dense vectors that the model can actually learn from.

## Math Notation: Your First Symbols

Two symbols you'll see everywhere in ML:

**Sigma notation (Σ)**: "Add these up."

`Σᵢ xᵢ` means "sum all the x values" -- same as `Enum.sum(list)` or `Nx.sum(tensor)`.

The subscript `i` is the loop variable. `xᵢ` means "the i-th element" -- same as `x[i]` or `Nx.slice`.

| Math | Elixir/Nx | Meaning |
|------|-----------|---------|
| `Σᵢ xᵢ` | `Nx.sum(x)` | Add up all elements |
| `xᵢ` | `x[i]` | The i-th element |
| `n` | `Nx.axis_size(x, 0)` | Number of elements |

These will come back in every notebook. By notebook 10, you'll be reading full equations.

## Key Concepts

| Concept | What it means |
|---------|--------------|
| **Language model** | Predicts the next token given previous tokens |
| **Tokenization** | Converting text to numbers (and back) |
| **Vocabulary** | The set of all possible tokens |
| **Block size** | Maximum number of tokens the model can see at once (context window) |
| **Batch** | Multiple sequences processed simultaneously for efficiency |
| **Train/val split** | Separate data for training vs. measuring generalization |
